// ============================================================================
// ADVANCED OPTIONS
// ============================================================================

// Preserve boundary patches and interface
distributed     no;
roots           ();

// ============================================================================
// DECOMPOSITION STRATEGY NOTES
// ============================================================================
//
// Hierarchical method is recommended because:
// 1. Predictable domain decomposition
// 2. Good cache locality
// 3. Minimal communication overhead for structured mesh
// 4. Y-direction has most cells (1600+2400+72=4072), so decompose more in Y
//
// Decomposition ratios (for 128 cores: 8×8×2):
// - X: 250 cells / 8 = ~31 cells/subdomain
// - Y: 4072 cells / 8 = ~509 cells/subdomain
// - Z: 100 cells / 2 = 50 cells/subdomain
//
// Each subdomain: ~31 × 509 × 50 ≈ 789,000 cells
//
// For SCOTCH (automatic):
// - Better load balancing for irregular physics
// - Useful if material distribution becomes very uneven
// - Slightly higher decomposition time
//
// SLURM job submission recommendations:
// - For 128 cores: --nodes=4 --ntasks-per-node=32 (4 nodes × 32 cores)
// - For 256 cores: --nodes=8 --ntasks-per-node=32 (8 nodes × 32 cores)
// - Memory: ~4-8 GB per core (512-1024 GB total for 128 cores)
// - Walltime: 48-72 hours for complete LIFT cycle (2 ns simulation)
//
// Performance estimates:
// - ~0.1-0.5 seconds per timestep (depending on adaptive dt)
// - ~10^6 timesteps for 2 ns with average dt ~ 2 fs
// - Total runtime: ~100-500k seconds = 28-139 hours
//
// Scaling efficiency:
// - Strong scaling: Good up to ~800k cells/core
// - Weak scaling: Linear up to 512 cores for this problem size
//
// I/O considerations:
// - Use uncollated file handler (set in controlDict)
// - Binary format for faster writes
// - Consider reducing writeInterval for long runs
// - Parallel I/O bandwidth critical: use high-speed filesystem (Lustre/GPFS)

